# Internationalization Best Practices

Standards for implementing internationalization in Next.js applications. Auto-included for all TypeScript/React files.

<rule>
name: i18n_best_practices
description: Best practices for internationalization (i18n) in Next.js applications. Auto-included for TypeScript/React files.
globs: ["app/**/*.{ts,tsx}"]

filters:

-   type: file_extension
    pattern: "\\.(ts|tsx)$"
-   type: content
    pattern: "useTranslations|t\\(['\"]"

actions:

-   type: suggest
    message: |
    When implementing internationalization:

    1. Translation Files Structure and Location:
       - All translation files are located in `lib/i18n/messages/`
       - One file per language (e.g., en-US.json, fr-FR.json)
       - IMPORTANT: Only edit the en-US.json file
       - Other language files are auto-generated from en-US.json using our translation script
       - Never manually edit any language file other than en-US.json
       - Available languages are defined in the i18n.rules section of en-US.json
       - Default language is en-US

    2. What to Translate vs Not Translate:
       To Translate:

        - UI texts (titles, descriptions, labels, messages)
        - Error and success messages
        - Help texts and tooltips
        - Buttons and actions
        - Form placeholders
        - Form validations

        Do Not Translate:

        - Brand/product names (Apple, Android, Google Chrome)
        - Technical terms (HTML, CSS, JavaScript)
        - Standard terms (email, URL)
        - Timezone values, date/time formats
        - Country codes (FR, US)
        - Service names (Gmail, Outlook)
        - IP addresses, technical IDs
        - Units of measurement, sizes

    3. Translation File Structure:

        - Use hierarchical organization based on app sections
        - Use camelCase for keys (e.g., signOutAllDevices)
        - Use explicit names (prefer emailValidation over emailError)
        - Group translations by component/feature
        - Create sub-objects for related categories (e.g., validation.email)

    4. React Component Implementation:

        - Initialize useTranslations with complete namespace path
        - Prefer single initialization per component
        - Use specific namespaces to avoid naming conflicts
        - Use proper typings for translation functions to get type safety:
          ```typescript
          // In component:
          const t = useTranslations("components.sidebar.navigation");

          // When passing to other functions, use ReturnType for proper typing:
          function getItems(t: ReturnType<typeof useTranslations<"components.sidebar.navigation">>) {
            return [
              { label: t("dashboard"), value: "dashboard" },
              { label: t("settings"), value: "settings" }
            ];
          }
          ```

    5. Dynamic Elements and Rich Text:

        - For Zod validation schemas, use function parameters
        - For variable texts, use parameters in translation strings
        - For pluralization, use the ICU message format:
          ```json
          {
            "toast": {
              "deleteSuccess": "{count, plural, =1 {Item deleted} other {# items deleted}}"
            }
          }
          ```
        - For rich text with formatting (like bold or links), use custom tags with t.rich:
          ```json
          {
            "message": "The username <strong>{username}</strong> is available!"
          }
          ```
          ```typescript
          t.rich('message', {
            username: 'johndoe',
            strong: (chunks) => <strong>{chunks}</strong>
          });
          ```
        - Define reusable tag handlers for common formatting needs:
          ```typescript
          const richTextElements = {
            strong: (chunks: React.ReactNode) => <strong>{chunks}</strong>,
            link: (chunks: React.ReactNode) => <a href="/docs">{chunks}</a>
          };

          t.rich('message', {
            ...richTextElements,
            username
          });
          ```
        - AVOID using dangerouslySetInnerHTML for translations as it poses security risks
        - Use t.rich() to handle HTML tags in translation strings instead of manual string manipulation

    6. Translation Extraction Process:

        - Identify visible texts in component
        - Classify texts (needs translation vs invariant)
        - Organize by appropriate namespace
        - Extract dynamic parts as variables
        - Add to en-US.json file following structure
        - DO NOT edit any other language files
        - Replace static texts with translation function calls
        - DO NOT change the extracted english text, just extract for original

    7. Maintenance:
        - Check for existing translations before adding new ones
        - Use tools to detect unused keys
        - Document important namespaces in README
        - Only update en-US.json, other languages will be auto-updated

examples:

-   input: |
    // Bad: Hard-coded strings
    <button>Sign Out</button>

    // Good: Using translations
    <button>{t("signOut")}</button>

-   input: |
    // Bad: Multiple translation hooks
    const t1 = useTranslations("common");
    const t2 = useTranslations("auth");

    // Good: Single namespace
    const t = useTranslations("auth");

-   input: |
    // Bad: Using generic string type for translation function
    function getNavigationItems(t: (key: string) => string) {
      return [
        { label: t("dashboard"), href: "/dashboard" },
        { label: t("settings"), href: "/settings" }
      ];
    }

    // Good: Using ReturnType for proper typing
    function getNavigationItems(
      t: ReturnType<typeof useTranslations<"components.sidebar.navigation">>
    ) {
      return [
        { label: t("dashboard"), href: "/dashboard" },
        { label: t("settings"), href: "/settings" }
      ];
    }

-   input: |
    // Bad: Manual string concatenation for rich text
    <p>{t("prefix")} <strong>{username}</strong> {t("suffix")}</p>

    // Bad: Using dangerouslySetInnerHTML
    <p dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: t("message").replace("{username}", `<strong>${username}</strong>`) }} />

    // Good: Using t.rich with custom tags
    <p>
      {t.rich("message", {
        username,
        strong: (chunks) => <strong>{chunks}</strong>
      })}
    </p>

metadata:
priority: high
version: 1.4
</rule>
